Reasoning: 
- cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper deals with identifying the sparse principal component of a matrix, which is a common problem in machine learning and data analysis. 
- cs.IT (Information Theory): The use of auxiliary spherical variables and the analysis of the size of candidate index-sets may involve information-theoretic concepts. 
- cs.NA (Numerical Analysis): The development of an algorithm to compute the optimal sparse principal component in polynomial time requires numerical methods and analysis. 
- cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The algorithmic aspect of the paper may fall under this category, as well as the analysis of the size of candidate index-sets. 
- cs.SI (Social and Information Networks): Although less likely, the problem of identifying sparse principal components may have applications in network analysis and social networks.
